text of rivaling national aspirations and imperial policies. The analysis convincingly demonstrates the divisions within the nationalist movement, both politically between the moderates and socialists, and geographically between German-occupied territory with Vilna as a center versus Russian-controlled territory around Minsk. Besides the case study of Belarusian nation-building efforts, the book is a contribution to the study of the First World War in East Central Europe, approaching the war and its aftermath as a mobilizational moment in the region.  afunded by Opening the Future  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aNationalismzBelarus. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aBelarus.  aBorderlnds.  aEastern Europe.  aEmpire.  aNation-Building.  aNationalism.  aWar.2 aOpening the Futureefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2023z978311079759640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789633866344?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633866344zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633866344/original  a978-3-11-079759-6 Central European University Press eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA